Section 1:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 545
An Act to Exempt a Person Making Electrical Installations in the
Person's Existing Bona Fide Personal Abode from Licensing and
Permitting Requirements
Submitted by the Department of Professional and Financial Regulation pursuant to Joint
Rule 204.
Reference to the Committee on Housing and Economic Development suggested and
ordered printed.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative ROBERTS of South Berwick.
Printed on recycled paper
1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 32 MRSA §1102-C, sub-§5, as enacted by PL 2017, c. 198, §6, is amended
3 to read:
4 5. Exceptions to the permitting requirement. In addition to the exception for a
5 newly constructed single-family dwelling set forth in section 1102‑D, a permit from the
6 board is not required for:
7 A. An electrical installation in a single-family dwelling performed by a licensed
8 electrician qualified under this chapter;
9 A-1. An electrical installation performed by a person making electrical installations in
10 an existing single-family dwelling occupied by that person or to be occupied by that
11 person as the person's bona fide personal abode;
12 B. The electrical work and equipment employed in connection with the construction,
13 installation, operation, repair or maintenance of any utility by a public utility, or by a
14 contractor working on behalf of a public utility as set forth in section 1102, subsection
15 1‑C, in rendering its authorized service or in any way incidental thereto;
16 C. The electrical work and equipment employed in connection with an aboveground
17 electric transmission line described in section 1102, subsection 1‑B;
18 D. Minor repair work, including the replacement of lamps, fuses, lighting fixtures,
19 switches and sockets, the installation and repair of outlets, radio and other low-voltage
20 equipment and the repair of service entrance equipment;
21 E. Electrical installations for which a permit and inspection are required by municipal
22 resolution or ordinance under Title 30‑A, section 4173;
23 F. Any electrical equipment and work, including construction, installation, operation,
24 maintenance and repair in or about industrial or manufacturing facilities;
25 G. Any electrical equipment and work, including construction, installation, operation,
26 maintenance and repair in, on or about other properties, equipment or buildings,
27 residential or of any other kind, owned or operated by a person engaged in industrial
28 or manufacturing operations provided that the work is done under the supervision of
29 an electrical engineer or master electrician in the employ of that person;
30 H. Work performed by any person licensed under chapter 139 as an oil burner
31 technician, subject to the restrictions of the license as issued;
32 I. Work performed by a person licensed under chapter 139 as a propane and natural
33 gas installer, when installing propane and natural gas utilization equipment, subject to
34 the restrictions of that person's license;
35 J. Work performed by a person licensed under chapter 49 as a plumber, except that
36 this exception applies only to disconnection and connection of electrical conductors
37 required in the replacement of water pumps and water heaters of the same or smaller
38 size in residential properties; or
39 K. Work performed by a person licensed under chapter 69‑C as a pump installer,
40 except that this exception applies only to disconnection and connection of electrical
41 conductors required in the replacement of water pumps of the same or smaller size in
Page 1 - 132LR0632(01)
412 residential properties and the installation of new water pumps and associated
423 equipment of 3 horsepower or smaller.
3 Sec. 2. 32 MRSA §1201-A, sub-§11, as amended by PL 2011, c. 691, Pt. A, §34,
4 is further amended to read:
5 11. Wastewater treatment plants. Wastewater treatment plants, as defined in section
6 4171, and regular employees of wastewater treatment plants making electrical installations
7 in or about wastewater treatment plants; or
8 Sec. 3. 32 MRSA §1201-A, sub-§12, as enacted by PL 2011, c. 691, Pt. A, §35, is
9 amended to read:
10 12. Incidental work. Regular employees of an owner or a lessee of real property
11 doing incidental electrical work on that property or incidental electrical work by a person
12 whose occupation involves miscellaneous jobs of manual labor. For purposes of this
13 subsection, "incidental electrical work'' means minor electrical work, limited to light
14 fixtures and switches, that occurs by chance and that does not require electrical installation
15 calculations.; or
16 Sec. 4. 32 MRSA §1201-A, sub-§13 is enacted to read:
17 13. Personal abode. Notwithstanding the requirements set forth in section 1102-D
18 for electrical installations in newly constructed single-family dwellings, a person making
19 electrical installations in an existing single-family dwelling occupied by that person or to
20 be occupied by that person as the person's bona fide personal abode, as long as the
21 installation conforms with the standards of the National Electrical Code or other standards
22 approved by the board.
23 SUMMARY
2244 This bill reinstates the exception, inadvertently omitted from Public Law 2017, chapter
2255 198, allowing a person, without first obtaining a license or a permit from the Electricians'
2266 Examining Board, to make electrical installations in an existing single-family residence
2277 occupied by that person or to be occupied by that person as that person's personal abode
2288 that previously existed in the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 32, section 1105, former
2299 subsection 5. The installation must conform with the National Electrical Code and other
3300 standards adopted by the board.
Page 2 - 132LR0632(01)
